        How is Your Take-Home Pay Calculated?
      </h2>
      <div
        class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6"
      >
        <p>
          Understanding take-home pay requires dissecting gross compensation
          down to net income. When you review your paycheck, the number that
          hits your bank account is the result of a precise sequence of
          subtractions:
        </p>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li>
            <strong>Gross Salary:</strong> Your base hourly or annual compensation
            before any deductions or tax withholdings.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Subtract Pre-Tax Deductions:</strong> Voluntary employee contributions
            to traditional 401(k) accounts, traditional IRAs, health savings accounts
            (HSA), or pre-tax health insurance premiums. These contributions are deducted
            directly from your gross income, reducing your overall taxable basis.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Subtract Federal Income Tax:</strong> Underwriters compute federal
            tax liability by applying progressive tax brackets to your remaining taxable
            income (Adjusted Gross Income minus the standard deduction).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Subtract State Income Tax:</strong> If your state assesses a wage
            tax, progressive brackets or flat rates are applied to your income.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Subtract FICA Tax:</strong> Unlike income tax, Social Security
            (6.2% up to the wage limit) and Medicare (1.45%) are calculated on gross
            income, regardless of pre-tax deductions.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Net Take-Home Pay:</strong> The residual balance is your actual
            net salary distributed to you by check or direct deposit.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <h2
        class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mt-12 mb-6"
      >
        Federal Income Tax Brackets Explained (2026)
      </h2>
      <div
        class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6"
      >
        <p>
          The United States uses a progressive income tax system, meaning higher
          portions of income are taxed at progressively higher rates. A common
          misconception is that entering a higher tax bracket increases your
          rate across all income. In reality, only the income within each
          specific bracket range is taxed at that bracket's rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, under 2026 single filer bracket estimates (projected with
          a ~2.7% inflation adjustment), if you earn a gross salary of <strong
            >$75,000</strong
          >:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li>
            First, subtract the single standard deduction of <strong
              >$15,400</strong
            >, leaving a taxable income of <strong>$59,600</strong>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The first <strong>$12,100</strong> of taxable income is taxed at <strong
              >10%</strong
            > = $1,210.00.
          </li>
          <li>
            The next chunk from <strong>$12,100 to $49,250</strong> ($37,150) is taxed
            at <strong>12%</strong> = $4,458.00.
          </li>
          <li>
            The remaining taxable income from <strong>$49,250 to $59,600</strong
            > ($10,350) is taxed at <strong>22%</strong> = $2,277.00.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Total Federal Income Tax:</strong> $1,210.00 + $4,458.00 + $2,277.00
            = <strong>$7,945.00</strong>.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          This single borrower pays an effective federal tax rate of
          approximately 10.6% ($7,945.00 ÷ $75,000.00), even though their top
          marginal bracket is 22%.
        </p>
      </div>

